A fun way of Counting

This is a fun way to teach students how to count. They will have a tactile experience and be able to have a hands on experience, which all kids love.

5th Grade Mathematics Lesson Plan

5th Grade Mathematics Custom lesson plan – February 2018
Overview
The purpose of this lesson is to explore the mathematic realm with 3D printing. Students will use Tinkercad and Thingiverse to create letters and numbers that will help them understand writing, reading and evaluating expressions in which letters stand for.
Standards
2017 Kansas Mathematics Standards (Grades 5)
• 6.EE.2 Write, read, and evaluate expressions in which letters stand for numbers.
o 6.EE.2a. Write expressions that record operations with numbers and with letters standing for numbers. For example, express the calculation: Subtract y from 5 which is . (6.EE.2a)
o 6.EE.2b. Identify parts of an expression using mathematical terms (sum, term, product, factor, quotient, coefficient); view one or more parts of an expression as a single entity. For example, describe the expression as a product of two factors; view as both a single entity and a sum of two terms. (6.EE.2b)
o 6.EE.2c. Evaluate expressions at specific values of their variables. Include expressions that arise from formulas used in real-world problems. Perform arithmetic operations, including those involving whole-number exponents, in the conventional order when there are no parentheses to specify a particular order (Order of Operations). For example, use the formulas to find the volume and surface area of a cube with sides of length . (6.EE.2c)
Objectives

  1. Students will identify with how to use the 3D printing in mathematics class.
  2. Students will understand how to write expressions in which letters stand for numbers.
  3. Students will understand how to read expressions in which letters stand for numbers.
  4. Students will understand how to evaluate expressions in which letters stand for numbers.
  5. Students will understand how to record operations with numbers with letters standing for numbers.
  6. Students will learn to use their own ideas to learn new material in class.
    Skills/Competencies
  7. Students will be skillful at using Thingiverse and Thinkercad.
  8. Students will use their imagination in order to create useful mathematic 3D prints.
  9. Students will need to be skillful at using the computer and the software.
    Essential Questions
  10. How is 3D printing changing the learning in mathematics?
  11. How is 3D printing helping students understand evaluating expressions?
  12. Do you understand how letters and numbers are used in recording operations?
  13. How can these operations be used in the real world?
    Makerspace Activity
  14. Students will sketch out their ideas on paper.
  15. Students will create a Thingiverse account.
  16. Students will create a Tinkercad account.
  17. Students will then explore with the teacher other persons’ ideas on Thingiverse for more ideas.
  18. The teacher will do a short tutorial of how to use Tinkercad.
  19. Students will then create their ideas in Tinkercad.
  20. The students will share their ideas and how they came up with them to the class.
  21. The submitting to Canvas will indicate they are ready to be printed.
  22. After printing is complete, the students work will be handed back to them.
    Additional Requirements
  23. Students will need a Tinkercad account.
  24. Students will need a Thingiverse account.
  25. Teacher prints the 3D product.

description.text:
Globoid worm gear drives

(code expects OpenSCAD 2018.1.6)

have several advantages over conventional worm gear drives. They significantly increase the contact area available for power transmission and allow for higher load capacity respectively reduced surface load and wear, which is essential for 3D printed parts. The downside is a very complicated calculation for both the globoid worm and the globoid gear when construction is done in an explicit fashion.

Printer:

I've made a test print with a i=15 system. It came out well in the end. The support structure for the worm was a bit nasty to remove, but I guess this was caused by the filament.

I've made a short video of the thing in action.

The idea - simulation of a subtractive process

With this project I want to show, how easy things can get, when construction is done implicitly by simulating a subtractive tooling process. Such a process involves a blank and a tool. When the tool is moved along a trajectory it carves its shape into the blank, wherever they clash. The result can be calculated by using a difference operation, where the tool is subtracted from the blank.

Let us start with the construction of the main tool, a simple 2D spur gear with z straight teeth. There is no point in using involute gearing, as no rolling between worm gear and worm occurs in a worm drive.
Using a sweep-operation lets us extrude this shape along a circle into a torus. During extrusion the 2D gear is simultaneously rotated around its own axis by exactly one tooth/per 360°. Differencing this slightly twisted donut from some cylinder centered within the torus will obviously produce a globoid worm.
A technical remark: The sweep() module used, does not allow for loop closing of moebius type designs. Therefore we create two half donuts and difference both of them from the cylindric blank.

With the globoid worm ready, we can use it as a tool to adversely craft the worm gear. It is sufficient (and also faster) to craft only one tooth by starting with a properly sized pie. The full blown wormgear can be constructed by a union of z rotated instances of that tooth.

Follow this little animation, to see the steps.

The code

is quite concise as it uses some of the most advanced OpenSCAD programming techniques to squeeze out the last and best OpenSCAD can do with respect to render time. Nothing for beginners, but a lot of stuff for more advanced programmers.

The main file globoidworm.scad of the project contains a well commented parameter section, allowing you to design systems with various ratios, heights and axis distances. Note that

  1. for some specific parametrizations the code can produce systems that can't be assembled any more, and thus have to be directly printed. So choose your parameters carefully und check the preview well before print.
  2. It can be advantegous to F6 render the system for inspecting it from all sides, as F5-preview can get quite slow especially for higher z values.
  3. For worm gear construction a single tooth is trimmed from both sides using a difference operation against an outer part of the worm's groove. The code does not calculate itself, which part of the groove will be the optimum. Therefore it is your responsibility to adjust the value of eng_t (engaged teeth) to the number of teeth that are roughly engaged. The code also takes a clearance in mm between the worm and the wormgear into account.
  4. I have added a puristic bracket for testing purposes. You may want to customize its design so that it will better fit your application scenario.
The libraries

The code heavily uses the latest versions of two of my favorite libraries which are more explicitly described and used in some of my earlier Thingiverse projects.

Shortcuts.scad defines simplifying synonyms for many important OpenSCAD keywords (affine transformations, Boolean operations, geometric primitives) as well as macros for additional primitives (loop types, geometric elements). Sorry for this additional severity, but it speeds up coding so much, and also enhances code readabilty, once you understood the naming convention.

Naca_sweep.scad provides all the stuff needed for constructing and knitting polyhedron objects generated from 2D-shapes being placed into 3D space along some user defined trajectory. In the current project sweep() is used to skin the half donuts from a sequence of 2D gears arranged as moebius-like toroid.

Both libraries offer a help_libname() module, which outputs the module prototypes to the console.

Finally, I have to note that I have tested the code with different versions of OpenSCAD. The official 2015.3 as well as a couple of older snapshots like from late 2017 won't work and report some CGAL errors. The currently newest development snapshot 2018.1.6. which you get from http://www.openscad.org/downloads.html#snapshots will do.

The WAAAGH! is the name given by the Orks themselves to the massive military campaigns they periodically unleash on the galaxy as part of their eternal desire to seek out combat and war. The term also applies to the key concept of Ork "kultur" around which the entire Greenskin society, if it can be called that, revolves. Barbaric and savage, the Greenskins spread across the galaxy like a viridian stain. They plague the battlefields of the 41st Millennium in great numbers, overrunning any who stand before them in a torrent of bloodshed and usually mindless violence. An Ork WAAAGH! is war on an apocalyptic scale. Orks beyond counting swarm from one world to the next. Whole civilisations are exterminated and defenders' armies laid to waste as the Orks plough ever onward in an unstoppable tide. Orks need battle just as humans need food and drink. Due to their warlike nature, they constantly fight amongst themselves, or launch piratical raids upon nearby enemies. Such conflicts tend to be small-scale or localised. They never really develop beyond random outbursts of violence and looting. However, Ork populations can reach a critical mass that leads to a full-scale planetary migration. This is known as a WAAAGH!, a crusade of pure aggression that crashes through star systems in an orgy of violence.

Ork behaviour is dominated by the WAAAGH!, which is also the name given to the gestalt psychic field the Greenskins generate that affects the Ork psyche, which allows Orks to instinctively recognize who is "bigga", and therefore who is in charge, since might makes right in Ork society. All Orks generate this field, and it grows stronger as the Orks enjoy themselves, generally while fighting, and as more of them congregate together in one geographical area. The WAAAGH! helps give momentum to the Orks' planetary assault campaigns, which are also known as WAAAGHs! (the Orks like to call a lot of things WAAAGH!s). Such a WAAAGH! is a cross between a holy crusade and a pub crawl, with a bit of genocide thrown in for good measure. Thousands of Orks will gather together, drawn to the power of a single dominant Ork called a Warboss or Warlord if the WAAAGH! is particularly massive, who is bigger and more intelligent than the Orks around him. Then the Orks will set off to find an enemy to fight and defeat. Ork WAAAGHs! will sweep whole planetary systems away and destroy armies and fleets in tides of bloodlust and carnage, and only once the Orks have killed every available enemy will they start to fight amongst themselves again.

The Imperium of Man's Tech-priests have theorized that this gestalt psychic field also has a telekinetic or quantum probabilistic effect, allowing the seemingly ramshackle and poorly designed Ork technology to work as the Greenskins expect. It is believed that the reason this hypothesis came into existence is that the Imperium adopted the Adeptus Mechanicus' religious belief that aspects of a universal "Machine Spirit" inhabits all technology, and that this Machine Spirit serves Mankind at the command of the Machine God. If this is the case, without a Machine Spirit, Ork machines could not work, requiring some psychic cause to justify their often devastating effect. Furthermore, Mechanicus Genetor Lukas Anzion has noted that many Ork-built weapons will not function at all unless wielded by an Orkoid, possibly supporting this hypothesis.

Also note, you will want to print the split versions and glue, as you really need texture on both the top and bottom for these to work as stackers.

Painting the dungeon stackers

You can follow BMC's instructions, or, to get a result that look like mine, you need the following:

  • Krylon Flat Black Camo Primer (or other black primer)
  • Americana Zinc (or other dark grey)
  • Americana Burnt Umber (or other dark brown)
  • Americana Honey Brown (or other light brown)
  • American Slate Grey or Neutral Grey (or other light grey)
  • A sponge

Sadly, my first two pictures are lost, so here's the summery:

Glue the dungeon stackers together, using a hobby knife to smooth the seams (and putty if you want for additional smoothing). Prime them with black spray primer (I use Krylon Flat Black Camo Primer). Sponge on the dark grey heavily.

Do a lighter sponge on of the dark brown

Do an even lighter sponging on of the light brown

dry brush on your light grey, trying to catch the edges as much as you can.

I designed two different types of caps to close your Capsule with. You can choose between one cap with a huge handle to fasten TheCapsule on your backpack and the other, which is flat and has no handle on top in order to save some space while being stored in your bag.

To create your own “TheCapsule”:
You have to cut off the top of a standard 250ml drinking can with a tin opener (This shouldn’t be too difficult) and then press the threaded ring onto the opened drinking can (You can do this best by putting the threaded ring on a table and pressing the can onto the ring. -> The open side of the can has to pressed into the ring). The cap can now be screwed on the threaded ring and can be sealed up with a conventional rubber band or with a printable TPU sealing ring.
With a conventional rubber band TheCapsule 250 provides protection against splash water as well as rain or snow. If you use a TPU sealing ring you can even put TheCapsule 250 under water for a certain period of time.

description.text:
After doing some math the MK3 has a capped blower fan. Prusa limits the RPM to 4200. The low speed makes for a CFM, cubic foot per minute, that is about 3-4 which is very low. A 40mm Noctua has a CFM of about 12 which is 3-4X more powerful. This lack of output means the bigger the opening the less effective the shroud will be hence why there are cooling issues on the MK3.

Using a shroud like this takes the low pressure and increases it while directing that airflow directly at the filament it's trying to cool. Theoretically it should give you far better cooling but I haven't had time to run major tests so I'm hoping to get feedback.

Killa Kans bear many similarities to Deff Dreads, with their snipping klawz, chugging heavy weapons, and lumpy metal hulls. Yet in place of an enraged Ork, Killa Kans are piloted by cackling grots. Though individually smaller than a Deff Dread, Killa Kans charge toward the enemy lines in jostling mobs of riveted iron and roaring saw-blades. The Killa Kans' Grot pilots put their relative skill with firearms to good use, blowing the zog out of anything unlucky enough to cross their path. Despite being hardwired into a ten-foot tall killing machine, Killa Kan pilots still retain a good degree of Gretchin cowardice. As a result they still believe in safety in numbers, and have a bad habit of losing their nerve under fire. It is not unheard of for Killa Kans to waddle about in circles or freeze up entirely at the first sign of danger.

Killa Kans are smallish, bipedal walkers composed of a rickety, lightly armoured “kan” perched atop a pair of piston driven legs, and armed with a selection of ranged and close-combat weapons. Relatively primitive and weak by Ork standards, they are nonetheless fast and incredibly dangerous for their size, and one or two are more than a match for an Imperial Guard Sentinel Walker. As for the operator within, Killa Kans are not so much piloted as they are inhabited by a particularly ill-tempered Gretchin. Requiring the skills of both a Mekboy and a Painboy, fielding a Killa Kan entails first building the vehicle itself, then hard-wiring a volunteer Grot directly into the control systems. This painful procedure is not unlike the technology used in the creation of Space Marine Dreadnoughts, although significantly cruder and messier. Not only is the procedure excruciatingly painful, but implanting a Grot into a Killa Kan often increases the creature’s aggression and brute savagery by an inordinate amount.

No one can feel safe around a mob of Lootas - a brief scuffle with a Loota over a stolen thing will most often result to the previous owner finding his lunch, his Slugga and his golden teef are mysteriously missing. Because of it they are often found in Big Mek Warbands. Many Lootas are also affiliated with the Death Skulls clan who, being a dangerous band of grubby-fisted thieves, welcome their Loota brethren with open arms.

As a result of their attitude, Lootas tend to become pretty rich by Ork standards. They trade the best items in their possession for more and more powerful guns. Their main weapon is a Deffgun, a heavy shoulder-mounted gun, usually made by some known Mek from weaponry that the Lootas managed to steal or gather on the battlefield. In battle they gather in mobs, providing fire support with their deadly weaponry, sometimes accompanied by Meks, who want to see how their creations perform in battle. After the fight is over they scavenge the battlefield and strip weapons, armour and equipment from their enemy's dead, before selling the gear to the Mekboys.

Ork Stormboyz are the equivalent of greenskin shock troops. They have discipline above that of the average Ork and are more efficient too. Commonly viewed as being nutcases amongst regular Orks since they go into battle with fuel-filled rockets strapped to their backs. Orks usually distrust anything that flies and prefer to go to battle on their own two legs, but Stormboyz love nothing more than joining battle quickly, part of the reason they strap rockets to their backs.

Most Stormboyz are usually younger Orks who for various, inexplicable reasons, have grown tired of the normaly anarchic lifestyle among the regular Ork boyz. Tired of being told that they can do whatever they want they seek the way to rebel against typical Ork lifestyle. Longing for discipline, these youths often run off to join a Stormboyz camp. This is particularly typical of the youths of the Goffs and Blood Axe clans.

While at these camps the young Orks are drilled in marching and hurtling through the air, a regimental lifestyle that these Orks can become easily addicted to. It may be due to their chosen lifestyle that Ork Stormboyz have an actual respect for authority rare in Ork Kultur. Unlike most Orks, Stormboyz also take planning and forethought very seriously. Such information as strength and location of the foe are used by the Stormboyz to determine how best to orchestrate their attack.

Other Orks usually view all this parading, boot-polishing and voluntary obedience with amusement or even contempt, but despite their strange ways, the Stormboyz are a serious force on a battlefield. Always eager to show their prowess by putting their battle-drill into practice they use their Rokkit Packs to strike at vulnerable targets, predetirmined by a kunning plan. Stormboys are invaluable when assaulting bastions and defence lines as all Orks understand. As other Orks, Stormboyz fight in mobs, often lead by a Nob.[1]

An example of a famous, or rather in this case, infamous Stormboy is Boss Zagstruk, the ruthless leader of a band of Stormboyz known as Vulcha Squad. His reputation for being a merciless killer and a fanatical disciplinarian is the very manifestation of the Stormboyz doctrine.

title: Adjustable stand for microscope (or other stuff)

description.text:
Description

Holder / adjustable stand for light parts (< 1kg) such as a microscope. You can add other parts by adding a custom fitting with 2xM3 holes at 10mm apart. Has a knob for adjusting the height of the object, tighten nut to adjust friction. See the README file for more details.

Requires that you add some heavy rocks/scrap metal in the base for stability.

To print

1 x arm
1 x gear
1 x knob
1 x neck
1 x rack
(1 x plate - if you have the same microscope as me)
2 x leg

After printing, fill the triangular hole in the "neck" object with something heavy.
In my case I took old screws, nails and other left over scraps of metal and filled
in with epoxy. It gives a very stable and nice feeling to the stand.

The arm can be positioned forwards or backwards so that the center of mass of
everything is within the area of the "legs". You can test it by hanging it lightly by
from the arm (light fingers, a thread through the holes etc). If it tilts forward then
you need to move the arm further back. The effective distance you get is a combination of
what heavy stuff you filled the neck with and the weight of what you have mounted.

If you happen to have the exact same microscope as me you can use the "plate" to attach
it with, non-destructively. In other cases you need to design something else that fits
whatever you want to mount. Design it with two M3 holes separated by 10mm that can be
screwed onto the rack.

description.text:
These are some parts I designed for upgrading the CR-10 to have quick swapable steel build plates, held in place by magnets. I made three of the plates from a 1m by 0.5m sheet of 0.5mm steel. The idea being when one print finishes, you don't need to wait for the bed cool, just pull off the build plate, put the next on and keep printing. Once the build plate is removed it cools relatively quickly and the part can usually be removed by simply flexing the steel sheet. Also it eliminates the need for those pesky binder clips.

Additional Parts:
0.5mm thick steel plate 310mm x 320mm
8 Neodynium 32mm Disc Magnets (https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B077XPZLM9/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s01?ie=UTF8&psc=1)
LokBuild Build Surface (https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B077TZW218/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1), or though I imagine any brand would do.

The bracket goes under the bed to hold the magnets in place without having to use glue. Be aware that due to the thickness of the bracket it will compress your springs significantly. I quite like this as it makes the bed more solid, however depending on the type of hot end your using and and how it's mounted, it may make it difficult to use the glass bed but works perfectly for the much thinner steel sheet bed.

The rim is simply something to hold the sheet by when it's hot and just pushes onto one edge of the steel plate.

I printed both parts in PETG. I'm sure ABS would work well as well but don't know how well PLA would stand up over time so would probably avoid that personally but it's your call.

Thanks for the comment. Driver using AMC7135's - is a better solution if it is needed led brightness control, but it more expensive. Usually I need full brightness.
Iled = 0,6 A - forward current of the LED;
Vled = 3,7 V - forward voltage of the LED;
Vbatt = 4,1 V - voltage of 97% charged 18650 battery;
Resistor for limit current:
R = Vbatt-Vled / Iled = 4,1-3,7 / 0,6 = 0.7 Ohm;
Power dissipated by the resistor:
Pres = Iled^2 x R = 0.6^2 x 0.7 = 0.25 W;
Full power consumption:
Pfull = Vbatt x Iled = 4.1 x 0.6 = 2.46 W; Led has Pled = 2.46-0.25 = 2.21 W
Efficiency:
Pled / Pfull x 100% = 2.21 / 2.46 x 100% = 90 %;

The Open End version allows you to just lift the spool out of the bracket. The Closed End version does not. You can also choose between the wide or shallow version.
For the shallow version, I used the M8 bolt with each spool and tighten it on with the M8 nut. This recreates the rod. Note that these bolts will only work with the shorter front frame assembly.
Update realized that I had 2 of the same side frames, one should be an open top and the other a closed, depending on what your preference is.

  • spool with a larger inner circumference for a tighter fit to help eliminate big turns when pulling which can result in filament binding.The holes are for M8 bolts or rods (if desired).

  • (2) 8 mm bolts (uses 5/8" ratchet)
  • side frame with open end

title: Foam Terrain Stamp - Snow / Dirt - 1" grids

description.text:
I created a lot of foamcore terrain for large outdoor landscapes - I previously used balls of tin foil for texture and carved the grids by hand, with mixed results. This stamp allows you to make consistent grids without measuring/drawing/hand sculpting.

Here's how I make mine:

  1. Peel 1 backing sheet off dollar store foam board
  2. Lay on flat floor surface, place stamp in one corner, place board or book over stamp, and step on stamp - applying consistent pressure.
  3. Move stamp and repeat until board is covered. You can feel the impressions line up with the edges for consistent grids.
  4. (optional) Roll up tin foil into ball and press around sheet for more texture.
  5. Cut cardboard to size and hot glue to back of foam board for rigidity.
  6. (optional) for extra strength, hot glue around the edges, smeared with tip of glue gun
  7. Mod podge (mix acrylic color with mod podge for base cover and slather it on there).
  8. (optional) Wash with a paint/water mixture to add contrast and depth (black or dark brown for dirt, light blue for snow)
    DONE!

Just a note on this - this is the first of many stamps I plan to produce and was a prototype. The grid lines were a bit thick and take a lot of weight/pressure to get good impressions. For my next set I will make them thinner. so they can hopefully be hand-pressed easily. Also make sure to use a good amount of infill for strength (I used 50% I believe).

Will upload a finished ice sheet later today or tomorrow!

description.text: I needed a bracket for my Alunar M508 that would work with a Roko SN04-N inductive probe (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B076V1KDML/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1). I had ordered this by accident thinking that the M508 was the same as the Anet A8, just a different brand name. This was not the case, yes they are very similar, but structurally they are different. I was unable to find any brackets here in Thingiverse that would work, so made one of my own on Fusion 360.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

20%

Notes:

I printed mine with PETG, thought that since it would be sitting close to the hot end that I should use a material with a higher melting point.

Printing the bracket is pretty straight forward, and mounting it is pretty simple as well. Replace the two screws located above the extruder motor with some longer M4 screws. I had a couple of M4x12 screws left over from the M508 kit that worked perfectly.

Installing the sensor wasn't to difficult thanks to Exitoo. They have a nice wiring diagram located here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2234828. You will need a L7805CV L7805 Positive Voltage Regulator, and I got mine from Amazon. https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01M5L8C8Y/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1.

You will also need some way of connecting wires to the voltage regulator, either through soldering or by using a solderless bread board similar to this one found on Amazon. https://www.amazon.com/HiLetgo-Solderless-Breadboard-Protoboard-Prototyping/dp/B00LSG5BJK/ref=sr_1_13?s=industrial&ie=UTF8&qid=1517459641&sr=1-13&keywords=solderless+breadboard. They come in various sizes, and can just be mounted to the side of your printer with some double sided adhesive. Since I already had a soldering iron, I soldered the wires to my voltage regulator and then stuck it to the side of the frame near the main board using double sided tape, and that seems to be working fine.

Setting up the firmware was the hard part for me. First off I had to update the firmware, the stock firmware that comes with the M508 is not compatible with auto bed leveling. And it took me a good two days to figure out how to update to the latest version of Marlin. You will find the original stock firmware on the SD card that comes with the M508. As far as I know there is no way of making a backup of the firmware that's installed on the main board. I would make sure you have the original firmware in the event that something happens during the update and your printer isn't working properly. This way you can revert back to the original settings of the original firmware. I also highly recommend searching the internet with regards on how to update to the latest version of Marlin, especially if you have never updated your printer software before.

I found a program called Marlin Configurator that helped out a lot! It can be found here. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2403436. I had a hard time getting it work, so I may not be able to answer any questions with regards to the configurator, all I know is that I stumbled around a bit, and finally got it working. Once it was working, it was pretty simple to figure out from there.

Once the firmware is updated I recommend watching this video by Chris Riley, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G-TwWfUzXpc, I found it to be one of the easiest ones to follow and understand.

I hope all of this information helps, it's taken me a few days to get this all figured out, but it was pretty cool when the printer leveled the bed for the first time!!

PRZEKAŹNIK CZASOWY 0-999 MIN

Moduł przekaźnika czasowego oparty na układzie programowalnym. Jest to wielofunkcyjne urządzenie umożliwiające pracę w wielu aplikacjach.

Do wyboru mamy kilka trybów pracy :

1.P1.1

Po pojawieniu się stanu wysokiego na wejściu Triger następuje załączenie przekaźnika, i odliczany jest czas. Po odliczeniu czasu następuje wyłączenie przekaźnika. Ponowne przyjście Trigera w momencie odliczania czasu jest ignorowane.

2.P1.2

Po pojawieniu się stanu wysokiego na wejściu Triger następuje załączenie przekaźnika, i odliczany jest czas. Po jego odliczeniu następuje wyłączenie przekaźnika. Ponowne przyjście Trigera w momencie odliczania czasu powoduje jego zresetowanie i naliczanie od nowa.

3.P1.3

Po pojawieniu się stanu wysokiego na wejściu Triger następuje załączenie przekaźnika, i odliczany jest czas. Po jego odliczeniu następuje wyłączenie przekaźnika. Ponowne przyjście Trigera w momencie odliczania czasu powoduje wyłączenie przekaźnika oraz zresetowanie odliczanego czasu.

4.P2

Po pojawieniu się stanu wysokiego na wejściu Triger następuje odliczanie czasu opóźnienia załączenia (CL), po jego odliczeniu następuje załączenie przekaźnika na określony czas.

5.P3.1

Po pojawieniu się stanu wysokiego na wejściu Triger następuje załączenie przekaźnika po odliczeniu czasu (OP) następuje wyłączenie przekaźnika i odliczanie czasu przerwy (CL). Cykl powtarza się pętli tyle razy ile wynosi wartość parametru (LOP).

5.P3.2

Po pojawieniu się zasilania (nie ma znaczenia stan na wejściu triger) następuje załączenie przekaźnika po odliczeniu czasu (OP) następuje wyłączenie przekaźnika i odliczanie czasu przerwy (CL). Cykl powtarza się pętli tyle razy ile wynosi wartość parametru (LOP).

5.P4

Ustawienie parametru P4- powoduje, że czasy zaczynają odliczać w momencie zniknięcia stanu wysokiego z wejścia Triger (odliczanie czasu wyzwalane zboczem opadającym).

(Domyślnie czasy odliczane są od zbocza narastającego na wejściu Triger.)

Ustawienie parametrów:

Przytrzymać przycisk SET przez 2 s. i ustawić funkcję 1.1, 1.2, 1.3, 2, 3.1, 3.2 za pomocą przycisku UP, DOWN następnie nacisnąć SET i ustawić czasy przyciskiem UP, DOWN przytrzymać przycisk SET 2s.

Zmianę przecinku uzyskujemy poprzez naciskanie przycisku STOP podczas wprowadzania czasu i tak :

XXX. 1-999 s.

XX.X 0,1-99.9 s.

X.X.X. 1-999 min..

Dodatkowo możemy ustawić tryb uśpienia polegającym na wygaszeniu wyświetlacza jeśli w przeciągu 5 min nie przyjdzie Triger. Tryb ten ustawiamy poprzez przytrzymanie przycisku STOP przez 2 s. aż na wyświetlaczu pojawi się napis C-P. Powtórzenie tej operacji powoduje powrót do trybu normalnego i na wyświetlaczu pojawi się napis d-

Tig

I created a lot of foamcore terrain for large outdoor landscapes - I previously used balls of tin foil for texture and carved the grids by hand, with mixed results. This stamp allows you to make consistent grids without measuring/drawing/hand sculpting.

Here's how I make mine:

  1. Peel 1 backing sheet off dollar store foam board
  2. Lay on flat floor surface, place stamp in one corner, place board or book over stamp, and step on stamp - applying consistent pressure.
  3. Move stamp and repeat until board is covered. You can feel the impressions line up with the edges for consistent grids.
  4. (optional) Roll up tin foil into ball and press around sheet for more texture.
  5. Cut cardboard to size and hot glue to back of foam board for rigidity.
  6. (optional) for extra strength, hot glue around the edges, smeared with tip of glue gun
  7. Mod podge (mix acrylic color with mod podge for base cover and slather it on there).
  8. (optional) Wash with a paint/water mixture to add contrast and depth (black or dark brown for dirt, light blue for snow)
    DONE!

Make sure to use a good amount of infill for strength (I used 50% I believe).

Will upload a finished ice sheet later today or tomorrow!

title: D-Bot CoreXY Printer with Extra Large 17"X17" Build Plate

description.text:
EDIT 2/7/2018 Keep in mind that the Bill of Materials and build guide are just copies of the same thing from the original D-bot CoreXY Thing. I didn't edit them or add any additional parts. So keep that in mind when ordering. Especially the V-slot rails. You will need more than the guide says. Probably about half a meter of 20x40 extra should cover it.

This is the extruder it's designed to use, but you could use the standard D-bot CoreXY bowden if you wanted to. Just be sure to print the right mounting plate for the X carriage. The holes are different on mine to fit this: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:760444

EDIT 2/1/2018 Oh. I forgot to mention. For some reason my X axis is reversed and I can't figure out why. So if you use my firmware you will have to mirror all non-symmetrical parts in your slicer.
If you solve this let me know how!

There will be more information added later, but for now you can use the Sketchup model to figure almost everything out. All V-slot rails are correct length in the model and the ones laid off to the side are the best combination I found for the cuts with as little waste as possible.

I think the second rail in the front of the build plate that I added is NOT included in the rails layout off to the side. So make sure you account for that rail when ordering V-slot.
Also you will need more rollers and screws etc for the front rail on the bed.
I HIGHLY recommend you use the added rail in the front.

The bed is VERY heavy so you will need to order Z axis steppers with gear boxes on them.
These are the steppers I used. https://www.ebay.com/itm/US-Ship-14-1-Planetary-Gearbox-High-Torque-Nema-17-Stepper-CNC-Robot-3D-Printer/331601658649?epid=10012076645&hash=item4d34ffc319:g:dxgAAOSwDNdVmx48

I have included my Marlin firmware in the files and it should be pre-calibrated.
It's set up for dual extruders even though there is only 1 so you will have to put a dummy thermister on extruder 2 pins or edit it to board type 33 and number of extruders 1 in configuration.h.

The 4 heated beds are wired in pairs. Put two beds on each power supply in parallel. For the bed temperature thermister you will need to wire 4 of them in series parallel. So put two in series with each other and the other two in series with each other. Then connect the two sets in parallel with each other so the resulting resistance is 100K. Then hook that to the bed temp pins on your Ramps board. If you don't understand this look at this schematic but ignore the values. All 4 would be 100K ohms. https://sub.allaboutcircuits.com/images/00123.png
When your Ramps reads the bed temperature it's not really reading each one and making sure they are all the same. it's reading the AVERAGE temperature of all 4. So be warned. If your heaters are not perfectly identical (they won't be) you may have slight variation of temp on your bed. It's pretty close though and the thick 1/4" glass will even out the heat if you let it sit for a bit and warm up.

You will need two solid state relays because you will be using two separate power supplies to power the bed heaters in pairs. Wire the inputs of the relays both to the 12V bed terminals on your Ramps together. So it turns both relays on and off at the same time.

I'm sure there will be lots of questions but those are the main differences between this and the regular D-bot.
It's been quite a while since I built mine and some of the files might be different versions of the same thing. You would really have the best luck if you opened the Sketchup model and just exported all your own STL files as those are probably all the final design. But if you can't do that I THINK the files I uploaded are complete.

Message me if you have any questions. If you post a comment I will probably miss it or not see it for a long time, so message me. Or look me up on Facebook. My name is Amadon Faul.

description.text:
UPDATE:

FIRST TEST SUCCESSFUL!! :-)

Working on making the horns in 2 piece prints if needed

The initial model by MustangDave is how this began, but I really liked the re sculpted version by Geoffro. I wanted to make a happy medium of each, then edit it to make just a head bust. So, here we are. :-)

Geoffro made a superb model of the Terror Dog. Only problem for me, was there were way to many polygons forming the model. It made working with the model difficult. I used the reduce command in mesh mixer to drop it just enough, as to not bog down my computer or software, not too mention, there are now less chances of errors popping up in your slicing software due to the massive amount of polygons from the previous model. (this was a learning process for me, so humor me)

I think I found a happy medium between MustangDave and Geoffro's work, and made a decent resolution model and so far it's doing great.

"INSTRUCTIONS"

If you take all the "TD CUT" files, and drag them into the program Netfab or even Netfab basic, all at once, it will give you the "puzzled together" look that some of my pics show. Doing this, will make it easier to identify each part, when it's time to fuse them all together. Just highlight each part in Netfab, and it will tell you which one it is.

"PRINTING"

Since this is a work in progress, and I'm still in the printing process, let me tell you what I used to save filament usage, and you can go from there. ;-) For each file, I've set my layer thickness to .04 instead of a .03 or .02
I didn't think it was necessary to have fine layer thicknesses for a large print like this. I'll explain why at the bottom of this summary.
The infill is entirely up to you. I've been toying around with virtually hollow infill settings. Currently, I'm using .03 for the infill. (again, knowing your printer capabilities will really help)

"THE PRINT FILES"

TDCUT 1 and TDCUT 7 are the horns. Everything else has been cut and quartered down to allow printing each part on a 10" print bed possible.

The files themselves, start out small in size. Use your printer slicing software to adjust the scale size of each printed part to your liking. BUT REMEMBER THAT SCALE SIZE!!! It will have to be the same for each part.

For me, I stared with TD cut2 point 1 and have been progressing from there. For my Robo R1 Plus model printers, I've set my scaling for each piece 15 X bigger than the file as it's dropped into my print field.

The scaling is entirely up to the person printing. I assume no responsibility for damage to a printer, if the person printing is unaware of the build volume their printer supports.

As each part prints out, you may see various pin holes in your printed "puzzle pieces" if your infill is too light. For me, I'm not worried about this because the final product in the end, will have filler in any holes before painting and finishing. I did this with a large Slimer and it worked great!!!

In all there are 22 files to print this out. For me, (and very much like other massive prints I've done this way) I'm a firm believer in Gorilla Epoxy!!

When all the piece are complete, Gorilla Epoxy can be your "adhesive" of choice since the stuff works outstanding with PLA plastic.

Now, remember the pin hole comment above? Using a body filling agent like spot filler (Bondo makes a tube of it that works great) can fill any minor holes the print may have produced due to thin infill settings and such.

Again, this is all up to the person printing the model, as well as their final detailing methods. I've made a number of full scale props such as this.....some of which I will continue to add to my list here....and my methods shared here, have produced OUTSTANDING results so far.

An extra tip which I think will help in the long run. Use a sharpie or something to label each print when done. I have notice this thing is like a jig saw puzzle from hell if you don't keep track of each part.

lol

Just remember your scaling, and the tips about using Netfab for assembly process.

Good luck.

Mike

description.text:
INSTRUCTIONS:

This is a remixed, cut up, and edited version of MustangDave's original Slimer print.

Like my life size Terror Dog head remix, this is basically the same set of instructions and methods.

In a nutshell, you are basically making a puzzle from the printed parts here to assemble into a large scale version of Slimer.

Supports WILL BE NEEDED on specific parts. Just look at the part you are printing, and if it looks like it needs them.....use them. ;-)

RE SIZING and ROTATING parts:

Be aware of your printer's build volume. As the parts are dragged into your print window for printing, they will initially be very small in size. These Slimer parts and pieces were resized to 3.5X the original file size. This may differ between various printers and their respective build volume, so please be aware of your available space for printing.

Certain parts are better off rotated for printer friendliness versus using unwanted support material.

I assume no responsibility for a damaged printer, if the builder is not aware of their build volume. What I did was to take each Slimer file, and drop it into my software and resize and rotate each one, one at a time to see if they would all fit. When done, I had 12 "Slimer pieces" that were assembled into the finished pic shared here.

Dragging all the Slimer files into Netfab, will show how all the final pieces are assembled together. To each their own process, but I have said....I am a firm believer in Gorilla Epoxy for projects like these. Then using various body fillers like spot putty or something close is very helpful.

I myself don't like the idea of overworking my 2 printers I have, but they have performed beautifully. Many of these full scale prints, I purposely use layer thicknesses like .04 and hollow infill settings like .03 to .05 because for me, the printing is not the final stage. I use fillers and such for final touch ups and using a product like those Bondo tubes sold, where mixing is not necessary, makes EXCELLENT filler for the occasional pin holes or deviations and such.

Now granted, you "could" just crank up your printer settings and use the best of the best settings in terms of layer thickness, infill, wall thickness, etc. HOWEVER, you will have a very long and drawn out print process and use MUCH more filament.

For this Slimer, I used all these above mentioned methods to complete an awesome Slimer.

I painted him with many many coats of florescent green Plasti Dip spray which was amazing and even allowed him to bounce when someone dropped him. LoL Naturally, the face and mouth are hand painted.

Good luck folks!!

Tried, tested, great results!!!

NOTE:

I noticed the "file" view here on Thingiverse makes the stl files in the pic section appear rather low res. I'm not sure why, but the final printed and detailed slimer "The green complete photo" as well as the finished printed parts an body assembly pic, are from THESE FILES. If memory serves.....I printed all of them out with a layer thickness of .04 so even though the .stl files appear low resolution, the final result speaks for itself. ;-)

This guy obviously ins't glass-smooth....but neither was Slimer. :-)

The city of Blanos is a Persian-inspired city on the coast of a great desert in a 5th edition D&D game.

These pieces make the understructure of middle-eastern brick buildings. They are designed to be printed and assembled in the shape you desire, and then skinned with a cardstock layer which can be cut away to reveal brick in the desired locations. Attached is one example of how this style could look when completed. The doors and window shutters snap in place and should rotate within the frames, allowing you to much more easily make custom-shaped buildings with working doors and windows.

The left and right sides of each join are designed to be a perfect mate in any of the three orientations for a straight line or a squared corner. With a good printer, you should get nice, snug joints that need very little gluing to hold them together, although adding a building base would be a good idea out of cardboard or MDF.

This style is inspired by the buildings of 4Ground miniatures out of the UK and their incredibly detailed laser-cut building models.

description.text:
Hey Guys!

This is an introduction to my 110 size quad design.

These were my objectives:

  1. An affordable quad able to fly indoors.
  2. It needed to be robust (crash resistant)
  3. Have a clean design

There is much more to do in the design and testing of this thing. However, I wanted to share it in hopes of getting some suggestions.

My list of things to do:

  1. Create a latch for the lid.
  2. Create a battery mount.
  3. Create other hold downs and openings for electronics.

Over the next couple of weeks I will be testing and improving on this design. If you decide to start building thing please post images... Enjoy!

UPDATE: 7 Feb 2018
Over the last week I have made many small changes to this design which has required it to be completely reworked in Fusion 360 many times. What were the changes?

  1. I have resized the motor mounts to snugly fit an 8.5mm diameter motor. I printed the frame on multiple printers to check for discrepancies. (However your mileage may vary)
  2. There is now a raised ring inside the motor mounts to allow space for the wires. Now you can push the motors into the mounts without pinching the wires.
  3. The camera mount was enlarged (slightly) and tilted upwards at a 10 degree angle. This should help dramatically in forward flight.
  4. The arms were narrowed slightly to reduce thrust interference. It also dropped 2 grams from the overall weight of the frame with no noticeable loss in durability.

At this point I am waiting for some other parts to show up in the mail before I can test fly it. Although I am going to go out on a limb and say that at this point it should be more than good to go.

Check post printing for more details. The design does not include clearance. The Display board support needs a little support.

Remember this is NOT for the official Raspberry Pi Display. This is something I found on ebay. Starting with the Display spindle, check the fit into the stand pocket. It's nice if you can get a smooth fit here. The screen pivots here, tight makes I difficult to move, and loose, it can flop around. DO NOT force the screen into the slot or you may damage the screen :(. Sand and scrape until screen slides in smoothly. If loose, a few strips of masking tape. With the screen removed, sand and fit the display circuit board mounts. These need to be drilled and tapped (or self tapping) Not sure all these display boards have the same hole pattern.
